# Slate Research

Handle $ARGUMENTS.

Use this when Slate v2 needs external prior art, better testing strategy,
browser/native-selection/IME/paste proof ideas, pagination/virtualization
research, huge-document behavior/perf research, TypeScript/API/DX discovery, or
large OSS repo scans before patching.

This is not `slate-ar` and does not run Codex Autoresearch packets. It discovers
and synthesizes research, then promotes accepted leads to the right execution
owner. `slate-ar` modes run measured loops; `slate-research` decides what
evidence-backed loops, oracles, plans, docs, and fixes should exist.

## Core Take

Research is not chat browsing, and it is not AR execution.

Research is a resumable evidence system:

```txt
question -> registry -> queries -> leads -> read log -> score -> promote
```

If the search could touch many repos, issues, PRs, examples, or papers, create
the ledgers first. Future agents must resume from files, not from compressed
chat.

Research has higher default weight after major internal proof already went
green. Internal knowledge is not the ceiling. GitHub OSS usually has useful
answers if the search is managed like engineering work.

## Boundary

- `auto`: supervisor. Decides when a research checkpoint is needed
  and which promoted owner runs next.
- `slate-research`: discovery and synthesis. Owns web/GitHub/OSS search,
  ledgers, source reading, dedupe, evidence grades, scoring, and promotion.
- `slate-ar`: execution wrapper. Owns Slate defaults for measured
  `codex-autoresearch` packet loops in `Plate repo root`.
- `slate-ar quality`: executes an accepted quality-gap checklist through
  Codex Autoresearch. It does not own broad OSS discovery.
- `slate-ar gate`: repeats existing proof gates once a command/oracle exists.
- `slate-ar perf`: optimizes benchmark-backed performance targets.
- `slate-patch`: fixes concrete bugs or missing oracles.
- `slate-plan`: decides architecture/API shape.
- `issue-harvester`: owns exhaustive issue-by-issue external corpus closure.

Flow:

```txt
auto
  -> slate-research        # discover, dedupe, synthesize, promote
      -> slate-ar quality  # execute accepted quality_gap checklist
      -> slate-ar gate     # repeat existing proof
      -> slate-ar perf     # optimize benchmark target
      -> slate-patch       # bug/oracle fix
      -> slate-plan        # architecture/API decision
      -> issue-harvester   # exhaustive issue closure
```

Do not route `research`, `web/GitHub discovery`, or `OSS scan` directly to
`slate-ar quality` unless a quality-gap checklist already exists. Discovery
first belongs here; execution after promotion belongs to the target owner.

## Use When

- A Slate v2 problem repeats after local fixes and local tests still miss it.
- Architecture/perf lanes plateau without a concrete owner.
- The route needs better browser/native-selection/IME/paste/mobile proof.
- Pagination, virtualization, huge-document, table, selection, or clipboard
  behavior needs prior art.
- TypeScript/API/DX shape feels uncertain.
- A benchmark or oracle is weak and other projects may have better harnesses.
- A timed run has remaining budget and the next best move is discovery, not
  another blind patch.
- The user asks to search hundreds of repos, scale research, avoid duplicates,
  or turn external examples into Slate-native proof.

## Do Not Use When

- The user named one external issue corpus and wants exhaustive issue-by-issue
  closure. Use `issue-harvester` for ledger detection/resume, latest refresh,
  and unchecked-row processing.
- The user wants one narrow local bug fix with a live repro. Use `slate-patch`.
- The next safe move is an accepted runtime/API decision. Use `slate-plan`.
- The work is a measured packet loop with known target/checklist/command. Use
  the matching `slate-ar` mode.
- The only work left is measured perf packet execution. Use `slate-ar perf`.

External issue-harvest is the exhaustive version of discovery. Ordinary
autoresearch samples the strongest repos, issues, PRs, tests, and examples
until a concrete Slate v2 invariant or owner appears.

## Command Contract

Use a small TheGreenCedar-style state shape for research, but keep it
source-controlled and Slate-native:

```txt
setup -> doctor -> next -> log -> state -> promote-preview
```

- `setup`: create or resume the research artifact and ledgers.
- `doctor`: verify artifact freshness, dedupe health, source cleanliness,
  stale claims, raw-path policy, and whether a promoted owner is already named.
- `next`: choose the next query, repo batch, issue/PR sample, source slice, or
  promotion target.
- `log`: record source reads, leads, rejections, duplicates, and promotions
  before opening another shard.
- `state`: summarize counts, current verdict, strongest leads, blockers, and
  next owner.
- `promote-preview`: list candidate owner packets without patching runtime.

This command contract is conceptual until helper scripts exist. If prose keeps
failing, add Slate-native helpers before adding more paragraphs.

## Operating Contract

Start every research loop by recording:

- question and scope;
- stop rule;
- artifact path;
- expected promotion owner;
- current local evidence gap;
- explicit exclusions.

Search both web and GitHub when the topic is broad or current. Useful GitHub
surfaces include code search, issues, PRs, discussions, examples, benchmark
harnesses, browser test fixtures, and commit history.

Include OSS projects beyond the usual three when relevant: ProseMirror, Lexical,
Tiptap, CodeMirror, Milkdown, Remirror, Monaco, Quill, TipTap
extensions, document editors, browser editor test suites, pagination/
virtualization libraries, and TypeScript-heavy UI/runtime projects.

For code-level claims, treat web/GitHub hits as leads only. Clone or inspect the
real source locally before patching Slate. Never patch runtime from snippets,
issue titles, README claims, or vague discussions.

Do not copy incompatible code. Extract invariants, test cases, API shape,
benchmark technique, architecture pressure, and browser proof strategy. Write
Slate-native code/tests.

## Artifact Layout

Default durable layout:

```txt
docs/slate-v2/research/<date>-<topic>/
  README.md                  # question, scope, stop rule, current verdict
  repo-registry.tsv          # one row per repo/source
  query-ledger.tsv           # one row per query/search surface
  lead-ledger.tsv            # one row per candidate invariant/idea
  read-log.tsv               # exact files/issues/PRs read
  rejected-ledger.tsv        # deduped rejected leads with reason
  promoted-ledger.tsv        # leads converted to Slate proof packets
  shards/
    001-<theme>.md           # bounded batch summary
    002-<theme>.md
  sources/                   # tiny excerpts/metadata, not raw dumps
```

Use `docs/slate-v2/research/**` as the default Slate v2 research working set.
Keep raw cloned repos, huge issue JSON, large scraped pages, binary artifacts,
and throwaway downloads out of that tree. Store raw bulk under
`docs/research/raw/<date>-<topic>/` or an external clone path, and link it from
the docs ledger only when needed.

## Ledgers

Required ledgers:

- `repo-registry.tsv`: `repo_key`, `url`, `host`, `license`, `stars_or_signal`,
  `last_activity`, `topic_tags`, `local_path`, `status`, `score`, `notes`.
- `query-ledger.tsv`: `query_key`, `surface`, `query`, `filters`,
  `result_count`, `sampled_count`, `new_repo_keys`, `new_lead_keys`,
  `next_query`.
- `lead-ledger.tsv`: `lead_key`, `repo_key`, `source_ref`, `topic`, `claim`,
  `evidence_grade`, `novelty`, `applicability`, `proof_owner`, `next_action`,
  `status`.
- `read-log.tsv`: `source_ref`, `repo_key`, `kind`, `path_or_url`,
  `lines_or_id`, `read_reason`, `takeaway`, `lead_key`.
- `rejected-ledger.tsv`: `dedupe_key`, `repo_key`, `lead_key`, `reason`,
  `reopen_condition`.
- `promoted-ledger.tsv`: `lead_key`, `packet_id`, `slate_owner`,
  `test_or_benchmark`, `verification_command`, `decision`.

Deduplication keys:

- `repo_key`: normalized `host/owner/repo`, lowercased, without `.git`.
- `query_key`: stable slug from search surface plus normalized query.
- `lead_key`: `<topic>:<normalized invariant>:<proof family>`, independent of
  repo. Multiple repos can support the same lead.
- `dedupe_key`: normalized problem signature, not source title. Example:
  `selection:projected-native-double-highlight:visual-oracle`.

Before reading a repo deeply:

1. check `repo-registry.tsv` for an existing `repo_key`;
2. check `lead-ledger.tsv` for the same `dedupe_key` or `lead_key`;
3. if duplicated, append support to the existing lead instead of creating a new
   research branch;
4. if the lead was rejected, read its `reopen_condition` before spending more
   time;
5. if the repo is already cloned, reuse `local_path` and update `last_activity`
   and `status`.

## Shards

Work in batches of roughly 10-20 repos, 20-40 issues/PRs, or one focused theme,
whichever is smaller.

Each shard gets one `shards/NNN-<theme>.md` summary with:

- scope;
- sources sampled;
- top leads;
- rejected leads;
- duplicate leads;
- score changes;
- next query.

After every shard, update the ledgers before opening another batch. Stop a
shard early if it produces a concrete Slate-native proof packet; move to
promotion instead of collecting decorative links.

## Evidence And Scoring

Evidence grades:

- `A`: local source inspected plus runnable test/benchmark idea or exact source
  behavior.
- `B`: upstream issue/PR/test discussion with enough detail to map a Slate
  invariant.
- `C`: docs/blog/example that suggests a pattern but needs local validation.
- `D`: search result, README claim, or vague discussion. Use only to choose the
  next source, never to patch.

Score leads, not repos. Use `impact`, `novelty`, `applicability`,
`proofability`, and `risk`, each `0-3`.

Promote leads with:

```txt
impact + novelty + applicability + proofability - risk >= 7
```

Lower-score leads may be promoted only when they match a current user-reported
bug. Downgrade duplicates unless they add a new proof family, browser, edge
case, or benchmark method. Prefer testing/oracle and benchmark-method leads over
runtime architecture rewrites unless the runtime owner is already proven.

## Promotion Gate

Do not patch Slate directly from research. A lead must first become one of:

- `test-packet`: a Slate-native unit/Playwright/Browser oracle with focused
  verification command;
- `benchmark-packet`: a metric or harness repair with target and before/after
  command;
- `plan-packet`: a `slate-plan` decision row when runtime/API ownership is
  unclear;
- `docs-packet`: accepted durable research note or current-state decision;
- `no-code-decision`: rejected/quarantined with reason and reopen condition.

If a research packet finds a likely fix, convert it into a normal patch, perf,
oracle, or plan packet with baseline, proof gate, and keep/revert/quarantine
decision.

If research finds no usable lead, keep the artifact with rejected leads and the
next search angle. A clean negative result prevents repeated wandering.

## Context Budget

Never stream hundreds of search results, issue bodies, or repo file matches into
chat. Save compact ledgers and shard summaries under
`docs/slate-v2/research/**`; save raw bulk under `docs/research/raw/**` and
inspect slices.

Prefer `gh search`, GitHub search URLs, repo metadata, `rg --files`, and short
source slices over full dumps. Clone only repos that have a scored lead or
likely unique source. For broad scans, use shallow clones where possible and
record the commit/ref.

If a search needs more than one context window, the ledgers are the state.
Resume from `query-ledger.tsv` and `lead-ledger.tsv`, not from memory.

## Closeout

Final handoff must include:

- repos searched;
- repos deeply read;
- issues/PRs read;
- leads kept;
- duplicates merged;
- rejected leads;
- promoted packets;
- top promoted leads with `lead_key`, evidence grade, owner, and proof command;
- top rejected leads when the rejection prevents repeated work;
- next search shard, or `none` with reason;
- changed list;
- workflow slowdowns;
- needs-user-attention;
- stopping checkpoints.

If autoresearch itself becomes slow or duplicate-heavy, log a workflow-slowdown
row and repair this skill or the helper script. The research system must get
sharper after every large search.
